 land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Poultney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Pountney  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Pountney","meanings":["English: locative name from Poultney (Leics), which is recorded as  <i>Pontenei</i> in 1086 and  <i>Pulteney</i> in 1220. The place-name derives from an Old English personal name * <i>Pulta</i> (genitive * <i>Pultan</i>) + Old English  <i>ēg</i> ‘island, piece of dry ground in a fen’."]}]},{"name":"Nigel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of the medieval name <i>Nigellus</i>, a Latinized version (ostensibly representing a diminutive of Latin <i>niger</i> ‘black’) of the vernacular <i>Ni(h)el</i>, i.e.   Neil .  Although it is frequently found in medieval records, this form was probably not used in everyday life before its revival by antiquarians such as  Sir Walter  Scott in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Nigel de Poultney I was born about 1184, in Misterton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs. Nigel De Poultney about 1209, in Misterton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1184–":"umbes 1184–Surnud","1188–Female":"1188–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1184–Male":"1184–Surnud","Abt 1184":"umbes 1184","Abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1210":"1210","1188":"1188","1184":"1184","Abt 1209":"umbes 1209","Misterton, Leicestershire, England":"Misterton, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Misterton, Leicestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Misterton, Leicestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1184–":"noin 1184–Kuollut","1188–Female":"1188–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1184–Male":"1184–Kuollut","Abt 1184":"noin 1184","Abt 1210":"noin 1210",